icipate in any of these Third Party Competitions, you are responsible for reading and ensuring that you understand the applicable rules and any eligibility requirements and are lawfully able to participate in such Third Party Competitions in your country of residence. If you wish to run your own Third Party Competition on the Platform, you are free to do so provided you comply with our Competition Terms.\r\n\r\n8.Termination\r\n\r\n8.1. Termination upon Notice. Either party may terminate this agreement at any time by notifying the other party.\r\n\r\n8.2. Termination by the Company. The Company may terminate or suspend your access to or ability to use the Site immediately, without prior notice or liability, for any reason or no reason, including breach of this agreement. In particular, the Company may immediately terminate or suspend accounts that have been flagged for repeat copyright infringement.\r\n\r\n8.3. Effect of Termination. Upon termination of your access to or ability to use the Site, your right to use or access the Site will immediately cease.\r\n\r\n8.4. Survival of Provisions. This agreements provisions that by their nature should survive termination shall survive termination, including, without limitation, ownership provisions, warranty disclaimers, and limitations of liability. Termination of your access to and use of the Site shall not relieve you of any obligations arising or accruing prior to termination or limit any liability that you otherwise may have to the Company or any third party.\r\n\r\n9.Disclaimers. The Site is provided as is, without any warranties of any kind.To the fullest extent permissible under applicable law, the Company disclaims all such warranties, express or implied, including, but not limited to, warranties of merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, non-infringement, accuracy, freedom from errors, suitability of content, or availability.\r\n\r\n10.Limitation of Liability. To the fullest extent permitted by applicable law in no event shall the Company be liable for:\r\n\r\n10.1. any direct, special, indirect or consequential damages, or\r\n\r\n10.2. any other damages of any kind, including but not limited to loss of use, loss of profits or loss of data, whether in an action in contract, tort (including but not limited to negligence) or otherwise, arising out of or in any way connected with the use of or inability to use the Site, including without limitation any damages caused by or resulting from reliance by user on any information obtained from Site, or that result from mistakes, omissions, interruptions, deletion of files or email, errors, defects, viruses, delays in operation or transmission or any failure of performance.\r\n\r\n11.Indemnification. You agree to defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Company, its subsidiaries and affiliated companies, and their officers, directors, employees, contractors and agents from and against any and all claims, causes of action, damages, obligations, losses, liabilities, costs or debt, and expenses (including attorneys fees and costs) and all amounts paid in settlement arising from or relating to use of the Site. The Company may assume the exclusive defense and control of any matter for which users have agreed to indemnify the Company and you agrees to assist and cooperate with the Company in the defense or settlement of any such matters.\r\n\r\n12.Arbitration\r\n\r\n12.1. Claim Procedure. For any dispute you have with the Company, you agree to first contact the Company and attempt to resolve the dispute informally. If the Company has not been able to resolve the dispute with you informally, we each agree to resolve any claim, dispute, or controversy (excluding claims for injunctive or other equitable relief) arising out of or in connection with or relating to this agreement by binding arbitration by the American Arbitration Association (AAA) under the Commercial Arbitration Rules and Supplementary Procedures for Consumer Related Disputes then in effect for the AAA, except as provided herein.\r\n\r\n12.2. Arbitration Location. Unless you and the Company agree otherwise, the arbitration will be conducted in the county where you reside.\r\n\r\n12.3. Arbitration Fees. Each party will be responsible for paying any AAA filing, administrative and arbitrator fees in accordance with AAA rules, except that the Company will pay for your reasonable filing, administrative, and arbitrator fees if your claim for damages does not exceed $75,000 and is non-frivolous (as measured by the standards set forth in Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11(b)).\r\n\r\n12.4. Arbitration Award. The award rendered by the arbitrator shall include costs of arbitration, reasonable attorneys fees and reasonable costs for expert and other witnesses, and any judgment on the award rendered by the arbitrator may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction.\r\n\r\n12.5. Injunctive Relief. Nothing in this Section shall prevent either party from seeking injunctive or other equitable relief from the courts for matters related to data security, intellectual property or unauthorized access to the Service.\r\n\r\n12.6. Class Actions. All claims must be brought in the parties individual capacity, and not as a plaintiff or class member in any purported class or representative proceeding, and, unless we agree otherwise, the arbitrator may not consolidate more than one persons claims.\r\n\r\n12.7. Waiver of Jury Trial. You agree that, by entering into these terms, you and the Company are each waiving the right to a trial by jury or to participate in a class action.\r\n\r\n13.Governing Law. This agreement will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Georgia, without regard to its conflict of laws rules.','Privacy Policy','','inherit','closed','closed','','336-revision-v1','','','2018-02-13 17:00:05','2018-02-13 22:00:05','',336,'http://codelabstudios.com/336-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(344,1,'2018-02-13 23:39:56','2018-02-14 04:39:56','','Portfolio','','publish','closed','closed','','portfolio','','','2018-02-14 04:27:34','2018-02-14 09:27:34','',0,'http://codelabstudios.com/?p=344',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(345,1,'2018-02-14 04:26:49','2018-02-14 09:26:49','','Services','','publish','closed','closed','','services','','','2018-02-14 04:27:34','2018-02-14 09:27:34','',0,'http://codelabstudios.com/?p=345',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(346,1,'2018-02-14 04:57:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2018-02-14 04:57:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://codelabstudios.com/?p=346',0,'post','',0),(347,1,'2018-02-14 04:57:36','2018-02-14 09:57:36','This privacy policy serves as a resource for those who are concerned with how their Personally Identifiable Information (PLL) is being used online. PLL, as used in US privacy law and information security, is information that can be used on its own or with other information to identify, contact, or locate a single person, or to identify an individual in context. Please read through our entire privacy policy carefully to understand exactly how we collect, use, protect, or otherwise handle your PLL in accordance with our website and US privacy law.\r\n\r\nWhat personal information do we collect from people that use our website, app, blog, or other services?\r\n\r\nWhen ordering or registering on our site, you may be asked to enter your email address or other details to help you with your registration. This can also be used for features such as resetting your password via sending a unique link to the email address you have on file with Codelab Studios.\r\n\r\nAt what times do we collect information?\r\n\r\nWe collect information from you when you register on our site, place an order, join our newsletter, download or enter information on our website.\r\n\r\nHow do we use your information?\r\n\r\nWe may use the information we collect from you when you register, make a purchase, sign up for our newsletter, respond to a survey or marketing communication, browse the website, or use certain other site features in the following ways:\r\n\r\n To personalize users experience and to allow us to deliver the type of content and product offerings in which you are most interested.\r\n To improve our website in order to better serve you.\r\n To allow us to better service you in responding to your customer service requests.\r\n To administer a contest, promotion, survey or other site feature.\r\n To swiftly process your transactions.\r\n To send periodic emails regarding your order or other products and services.\r\n\r\nHow do we protect visitor information?\r\n\r\nOur website is scanned on a regular basis for security holes and known vulnerabilities in order to make your visit to our site as safe as possible.\r\n\r\nSSL Certificate\r\nWe indeed use a SSL Certificate to better protect your information upon purchasing anyone of our products while on Codelab Studios.com\r\n\r\nDo we use cookies?\r\n\r\nYes. Cookies are small files that a site or its service provider transfers to your computers hard drive through your Web browser (if you allow) that enables the sites or service providers systems to recognize your browser and capture and remember certain information. For instance, we use cookies to help us remember and process the items in your shopping cart. They are also used to help us understand your preferences based on previous or current site activity, which enables us to provide you with improved services. We also use cookies to help us compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interaction so that we can offer better site experiences and tools in the future.\r\n\r\nWe use cookies to:\r\n Help remember and process the items in the shopping cart.\r\n Understand and save users preferences for future visits.\r\n Keep track of advertisements.\r\n Compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interactions in order to offer better site experiences and tools in the future. We may also use trusted third party services that track this information on our behalf.\r\n\r\nYou can choose to have your computer warn you each time a cookie is being sent, or you can choose to turn off all cookies. You do this through your browser (like Internet Explorer) settings. Each browser is a little different, so look at your browsers Help menu to learn the correct way to modify your cookies.\r\n\r\nIf you disable cookies off, some features will be disabled It wont affect the users experience that make your site experience more efficient and some of our services will not function properly.\r\n\r\nThird Party Disclosure\r\n\r\nWe do not sell, trade, or otherwise transfer to outside parties your personally identifiable information unless we provide you with advance notice. This does not include website hosting partners and other parties who assist us in operating our website, conducting our business, or servicing you, so long as those parties agree to keep this information confidential. We may also release your information when we believe release is appropriate to comply with the law, enforce our site policies, or protect ours or others rights, property, or safety.\r\n\r\nHowever, non-personally identifiable visitor information may be provided to other parties for marketing, advertising, or other uses.\r\n\r\nThird party links\r\n\r\nWe do not include or offer third party products or services on our website.\r\n\r\nGoogle\r\n\r\nGoogles advertising requirements can be summed up by Googles Advertising Principles. They are put in place to provide a positive experience for users. https://support.google.com/adwordspolicy/answer/1316548?hl=en\r\n\r\nWe use Google AdSense Advertising on our website.\r\n\r\nGoogle, as a third party vendor, uses cookies to serve ads on our site. Googles use of the DART cookie enables it to serve ads to our users based on their visit to our site and other sites on the Internet. Users may opt out of the use of the DART cookie by visiting the Google ad and content network privacy policy.\r\n\r\nWe have implemented the following:\r\n Demographics and Interests Reporting\r\n\r\nWe along with third-party vendors, such as Google use first-party cookies (such as the Google Analytics cookies) and third-party cookies (such as the DoubleClick cookie) or other third-party identifiers together to compile data regarding user interactions with ad impressions, and other ad service functions as they relate to our website.\r\n\r\nOpting out:\r\nUsers can set preferences for how Google advertises to you using the Google Ad Settings page. Alternatively, you can opt out by visiting the Network Advertising initiative opt out page or permanently using the Google Analytics Opt Out Browser add on.\r\n\r\nFacebook\r\n\r\nFacebook, as a third party vendor, uses Facebook Pixel to serve ads. This enables Facebook to serve ads to Facebook users based on their visit to sites they visit on the Internet. Please refer to Facebook Pixel for more information\r\n\r\nUsers will be notified of any privacy policy changes:\r\n On our Privacy Policy Page\r\n\r\nUsers are able to change their personal information:\r\n By emailing us\r\n\r\nHow does our site handle do not track signals?\r\nWe honor do not track signals and do not track, plant cookies, or use advertising when a Do Not Track (DNT) browser mechanism is in place.\r\n\r\nDoes our site allow third party behavioral tracking?\r\nIts also important to note that we allow third party behavioral tracking\r\n\r\nCOPPA (Children Online Privacy Protection Act)\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to the collection of personal information from children under 13, the Childrens Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA) puts parents in control. The Federal Trade Commission, the nations consumer protection agency, enforces the COPPA Rule, which spells out what operators of websites and online services must do to protect childrens privacy and safety online.\r\n\r\nWe do not specifically market to children under 13.\r\n\r\nFair Information Practices\r\n\r\nThe Fair Information Practices Principles form the backbone of privacy law in the United States and the concepts they include have played a significant role in the development of data protection laws around the globe. Understanding the Fair Information Practice Principles and how they should be implemented is critical to comply with the various privacy laws that protect personal information.\r\n\r\nIn order to be in line with Fair Information Practices we will take the following responsive action, should a data breach occur:\r\nWe will notify the users via email\r\n Within 7 business days\r\nWe will notify the users via in site notification\r\n Within 7 business days\r\n\r\nWe also agree to the individual redress principle, which requires that individuals have a right to pursue legally enforceable rights against data collectors and processors who fail to adhere to the law. This principle requires not only that individuals have enforceable rights against data users, but also that individuals have recourse to courts or a government agency to investigate and/or prosecute non-compliance by data processors.\r\n\r\nCAN SPAM Act\r\n\r\nThe CAN-SPAM Act is a law that sets the rules for commercial email, establishes requirements for commercial messages, gives recipients the right to have emails stopped from being sent to them, and spells out tough penalties for violations.\r\n\r\nWe collect your email address in order to:\r\n\r\nTo be in accordance with CANSPAM we agree to the following:\r\n\r\nIf at any time you would like to unsubscribe from receiving future emails, you can email us from our contact form and we will promptly remove you from ALL correspondence.\r\n\r\nAll of Codelab Studios paid sample packs &amp; paid sounds are 100% royalty free for personal use only. Contact us for commercial use. Reselling, redistribution and packaging is completely forbidden.\r\n\r\nWebsite Terms of Service\r\n\r\n1.Acceptance of Terms of Service. This is an agreement between Codelab Studios, (Company), the owner and operator of www.Codelab Studios.com (the Site), and you (you or You), a user of the Site. By using the Site you acknowledge and agree to these Terms of Service and the Privacy Policy, which is incorporated by reference. If you choose to not agree with any of these terms, you may not use the Site.\r\n\r\n2.Changes to Terms of Service\r\n\r\n2.1. Right to Change Terms. The Company reserves the right, in its sole discretion, to change these Terms of Service (Updated Terms) from time to time.\r\n\r\n2.2. Notice of Updated Terms. Unless the Company makes a change for legal or administrative reasons, the Company will provide reasonable advance notice before the Updated Terms become effective. You agree that the Company may notify you of the Updated Terms by posting them on the Site.\r\n\r\n2.3. Acceptance of Updated Terms. Your use of the Site after the effective date of the Updated Terms constitutes your agreement to the Updated Terms. You should review these Terms of Service and any Updated Terms before using the Site.\r\n\r\n2.4. Effective Date of Updated Terms. The Updated Terms will be effective as of the time of posting, or such later date as may be specified in the Updated Terms, and will apply to your use of the Site from that point forward.\r\n\r\n3.Use of Site\r\n\r\n3.1. License. During the term of this agreement, the Company grants you a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license to access the Site for your personal and non-commercial use in accordance with the Terms of Service.\r\n\r\n3.2. Intellectual Property Rights. The design, trademarks, service marks, and logos of the Site (Marks), are owned by or licensed to the Company, subject to copyright and other intellectual property rights under United States, foreign laws and international conventions. The Company reserves all rights not expressly granted in and to the Site. You agree to not engage in the use, copying, or distribution of any of the Site other than expressly permitted.\r\n\r\n3.3. User Conduct\r\n\r\n(a)You may not engage in any of the following prohibited activities:\r\n\r\n(i)copying, distributing, or disclosing any part of the Site in any medium, including without limitation by any automated or non-automated scraping,\r\n\r\n(ii)using any automated system, including without limitation robots, spiders, offline readers, etc., to access the Site,\r\n\r\n(iii)transmitting spam, chain letters, or other unsolicited email,\r\n\r\n(iv)attempting to interfere with, compromise the system integrity or security, or decipher any transmissions to or from the servers running the Site,\r\n\r\n(v)taking any action that imposes, or may impose at our sole discretion an unreasonable or disproportionately large load on Site infrastructure,\r\n\r\n(vi)uploading invalid data, viruses, worms, or other software agents through the Site,\r\n\r\n(vii)collecting or harvesting any personally identifiable information, including account names, from the Site,\r\n\r\n(viii)using the Site for any commercial solicitation purposes,\r\n\r\n(ix)impersonating another person or otherwise misrepresenting your affiliation with a person or entity, conducting fraud, hiding or attempting to hide your identity,\r\n\r\n(x)interfering with the proper working of the Site,\r\n\r\n(xi)accessing any content on the Site through any technology or means other than those provided or authorized by the Site, or\r\n\r\n(xii)bypassing the measures we may use to prevent or restrict access to the Site, including without limitation features that prevent or restrict use or copying of any content or enforce limitations on use of the Service or the content therein.\r\n\r\n4.Third Party Content. Through the Site, you will have the ability to access and/or use content provided by third parties. The Company cannot guarantee that such third party content will be free of material you may find objectionable or otherwise. The Company disclaims any responsibility or liability related to your access or use of any third party content.\r\n\r\n10.Privacy. For information about how the Company collects, uses, and shares your information, please review our Privacy Policy. You agree that by using the Site you consent to the collection, use, and sharing (as set forth in the Privacy Policy) of such information, including the transfer of this information to the United States and/or other countries for storage, processing, and use by the Company.\r\n\r\n5.Copyright Policy. The Company respects the intellectual property rights of others and expects users of the Service to do the same. We will respond to notices of alleged copyright infringement that comply with applicable law and are properly provided to us. If you believe that your Content has been copied in a way that constitutes copyright infringement, please provide our copyright agent with the following information in accordance with the Digital Millennium Copyright Act:\r\n\r\n5.1. a physical or electronic signature of the copyright owner or a person authorized to act on their behalf,\r\n\r\n5.2. identification of the copyrighted work claimed to have been infringed,\r\n\r\n5.3. identification of the material that is claimed to be infringing or to be the subject of infringing activity and that is to be removed or access to which is to be disabled, and information reasonably sufficient to permit us to locate the material,\r\n\r\n5.4. your contact information, including your address, telephone number, and an email address,\r\n\r\n5.5. a statement by you that you have a good faith belief that use of the material in the manner complained of is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law, and\r\n\r\n5.6. a statement that the information in the notification is accurate, and, under penalty of perjury, that you are authorized to act on behalf of the copyright owner.\r\n\r\n6.Trademarks. The Company name and logo are trademarks of the Company, and may not be copied, imitated or used, in whole or in part, without the prior written permission of the Company, except in accordance with our brand guidelines. In addition, all page headers, custom graphics, button icons and scripts are service marks, trademarks, and trade dress of the Company, and may not be copied, imitated, or used, in whole or in part, without prior written permission from the Company.\r\n\r\n7.Promotions. Some users may promote competitions, promotions, prize draws and other similar opportunities on the Site (Third Party Competitions). The Company is not the sponsor or promoter of these Third Party Competitions and does not bear any responsibility or liability for the actions or inactions of any third parties who organize, administer or are otherwise involved in any of promotion of these Third Party Competitions. If you wish to participate in any of these Third Party Competitions, you are responsible for reading and ensuring that you understand the applicable rules and any eligibility requirements and are lawfully able to participate in such Third Party Competitions in your country of residence. If you wish to run your own Third Party Competition on the Platform, you are free to do so provided you comply with our Competition Terms.\r\n\r\n8.Termination\r\n\r\n8.1. Termination upon Notice. Either party may terminate this agreement at any time by notifying the other party.\r\n\r\n8.2. Termination by the Company. The Company may terminate or suspend your access to or ability to use the Site immediately, without prior notice or liability, for any reason or no reason, including breach of this agreement. In particular, the Company may immediately terminate or suspend accounts that have been flagged for repeat copyright infringement.\r\n\r\n8.3. Effect of Termination. Upon termination of your access to or ability to use the Site, your right to use or access the Site will immediately cease.\r\n\r\n8.4. Survival of Provisions. This agreements provisions that by their nature should survive termination shall survive termination, including, without limitation, ownership provisions, warranty disclaimers, and limitations of liability. Termination of your access to and use of the Site shall not relieve you of any obligations arising or accruing prior to termination or limit any liability that you otherwise may have to the Company or any third party.\r\n\r\n9.Disclaimers. The Site is provided as is, without any warranties of any kind.To the fullest extent permissible under applicable law, the Company disclaims all such warranties, express or implied, including, but not limited to, warranties of merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, non-infringement, accuracy, freedom from errors, suitability of content, or availability.\r\n\r\n10.Limitation of Liability. To the fullest extent permitted by applicable law in no event shall the Company be liable for:\r\n\r\n10.1. any direct, special, indirect or consequential damages, or\r\n\r\n10.2. any other damages of any kind, including but not limited to loss of use, loss of profits or loss of data, whether in an action in contract, tort (including but not limited to negligence) or otherwise, arising out of or in any way connected with the use of or inability to use the Site, including without limitation any damages caused by or resulting from reliance by user on any information obtained from Site, or that result from mistakes, omissions, interruptions, deletion of files or email, errors, defects, viruses, delays in operation or transmission or any failure of performance.\r\n\r\n11.Indemnification. You agree to defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Company, its subsidiaries and affiliated companies, and their officers, directors, employees, contractors and agents from and against any and all claims, causes of action, damages, obligations, losses, liabilities, costs or debt, and expenses (including attorneys fees and costs) and all amounts paid in settlement arising from or relating to use of the Site. The Company may assume the exclusive defense and control of any matter for which users have agreed to indemnify the Company and you agrees to assist and cooperate with the Company in the defense or settlement of any such matters.\r\n\r\n12.Arbitration\r\n\r\n12.1. Claim Procedure. For any dispute you have with the Company, you agree to first contact the Company and attempt to resolve the dispute informally. If the Company has not been able to resolve the dispute with you informally, we each agree to resolve any claim, dispute, or controversy (excluding claims for injunctive or other equitable relief) arising out of or in connection with or relating to this agreement by binding arbitration by the American Arbitration Association (AAA) under the Commercial Arbitration Rules and Supplementary Procedures for Consumer Related Disputes then in effect for the AAA, except as provided herein.\r\n\r\n12.2. Arbitration Location. Unless you and the Company agree otherwise, the arbitration will be conducted in the county where you reside.\r\n\r\n12.3. Arbitration Fees. Each party will be responsible for paying any AAA filing, administrative and arbitrator fees in accordance with AAA rules, except that the Company will pay for your reasonable filing, administrative, and arbitrator fees if your claim for damages does not exceed $75,000 and is non-frivolous (as measured by the standards set forth in Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11(b)).\r\n\r\n12.4. Arbitration Award. The award rendered by the arbitrator shall include costs of arbitration, reasonable attorneys fees and reasonable costs for expert and other witnesses, and any judgment on the award rendered by the arbitrator may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction.\r\n\r\n12.5. Injunctive Relief. Nothing in this Section shall prevent either party from seeking injunctive or other equitable relief from the courts for matters related to data security, intellectual property or unauthorized access to the Service.\r\n\r\n12.6. Class Actions. All claims must be brought in the parties individual capacity, and not as a plaintiff or class member in any purported class or representative proceeding, and, unless we agree otherwise, the arbitrator may not consolidate more than one persons claims.\r\n\r\n12.7. Waiver of Jury Trial. You agree that, by entering into these terms, you and the Company are each waiving the right to a trial by jury or to participate in a class action.\r\n\r\n13.Governing Law. This agreement will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Georgia, without regard to its conflict of laws rules.','Terms of Service','','inherit','closed','closed','','338-revision-v1','','','2018-02-14 04:57:36','2018-02-14 09:57:36','',338,'http://codelabstudios.com/338-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(348,1,'2018-02-14 04:57:48','2018-02-14 09:57:48','This privacy policy serves as a resource for those who are concerned with how their Personally Identifiable Information (PLL) is being used online. PLL, as used in US privacy law and information security, is information that can be used on its own or with other information to identify, contact, or locate a single person, or to identify an individual in context. Please read through our entire privacy policy carefully to understand exactly how we collect, use, protect, or otherwise handle your PLL in accordance with our website and US privacy law.\r\n\r\nWhat personal information do we collect from people that use our website, app, blog, or other services?\r\n\r\nWhen ordering or registering on our site, you may be asked to enter your email address or other details to help you with your registration. This can also be used for features such as resetting your password via sending a unique link to the email address you have on file with Codelab Studios.\r\n\r\nAt what times do we collect information?\r\n\r\nWe collect information from you when you register on our site, place an order, join our newsletter, download or enter information on our website.\r\n\r\nHow do we use your information?\r\n\r\nWe may use the information we collect from you when you register, make a purchase, sign up for our newsletter, respond to a survey or marketing communication, browse the website, or use certain other site features in the following ways:\r\n\r\n To personalize users experience and to allow us to deliver the type of content and product offerings in which you are most interested.\r\n To improve our website in order to better serve you.\r\n To allow us to better service you in responding to your customer service requests.\r\n To administer a contest, promotion, survey or other site feature.\r\n To swiftly process your transactions.\r\n To send periodic emails regarding your order or other products and services.\r\n\r\nHow do we protect visitor information?\r\n\r\nOur website is scanned on a regular basis for security holes and known vulnerabilities in order to make your visit to our site as safe as possible.\r\n\r\nSSL Certificate\r\nWe indeed use a SSL Certificate to better protect your information upon purchasing anyone of our products while on Codelab Studios.com\r\n\r\nDo we use cookies?\r\n\r\nYes. Cookies are small files that a site or its service provider transfers to your computers hard drive through your Web browser (if you allow) that enables the sites or service providers systems to recognize your browser and capture and remember certain information. For instance, we use cookies to help us remember and process the items in your shopping cart. They are also used to help us understand your preferences based on previous or current site activity, which enables us to provide you with improved services. We also use cookies to help us compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interaction so that we can offer better site experiences and tools in the future.\r\n\r\nWe use cookies to:\r\n Help remember and process the items in the shopping cart.\r\n Understand and save users preferences for future visits.\r\n Keep track of advertisements.\r\n Compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interactions in order to offer better site experiences and tools in the future. We may also use trusted third party services that track this information on our behalf.\r\n\r\nYou can choose to have your computer warn you each time a cookie is being sent, or you can choose to turn off all cookies. You do this through your browser (like Internet Explorer) settings. Each browser is a little different, so look at your browsers Help menu to learn the correct way to modify your cookies.\r\n\r\nIf you disable cookies off, some features will be disabled It wont affect the users experience that make your site experience more efficient and some of our services will not function properly.\r\n\r\nThird Party Disclosure\r\n\r\nWe do not sell, trade, or otherwise transfer to outside parties your personally identifiable information unless we provide you with advance notice. This does not include website hosting partners and other parties who assist us in operating our website, conducting our business, or servicing you, so long as those parties agree to keep this information confidential. We may also release your information when we believe release is appropriate to comply with the law, enforce our site policies, or protect ours or others rights, property, or safety.\r\n\r\nHowever, non-personally identifiable visitor information may be provided to other parties for marketing, advertising, or other uses.\r\n\r\nThird party links\r\n\r\nWe do not include or offer third party products or services on our website.\r\n\r\nGoogle\r\n\r\nGoogles advertising requirements can be summed up by Googles Advertising Principles. They are put in place to provide a positive experience for users. https://support.google.com/adwordspolicy/answer/1316548?hl=en\r\n\r\nWe use Google AdSense Advertising on our website.\r\n\r\nGoogle, as a third party vendor, uses cookies to serve ads on our site. Googles use of the DART cookie enables it to serve ads to our users based on their visit to our site and other sites on the Internet. Users may opt out of the use of the DART cookie by visiting the Google ad and content network privacy policy.\r\n\r\nWe have implemented the following:\r\n Demographics and Interests Reporting\r\n\r\nWe along with third-party vendors, such as Google use first-party cookies (such as the Google Analytics cookies) and third-party cookies (such as the DoubleClick cookie) or other third-party identifiers together to compile data regarding user interactions with ad impressions, and other ad service functions as they relate to our website.\r\n\r\nOpting out:\r\nUsers can set preferences for how Google advertises to you using the Google Ad Settings page. Alternatively, you can opt out by visiting the Network Advertising initiative opt out page or permanently using the Google Analytics Opt Out Browser add on.\r\n\r\nFacebook\r\n\r\nFacebook, as a third party vendor, uses Facebook Pixel to serve ads. This enables Facebook to serve ads to Facebook users based on their visit to sites they visit on the Internet. Please refer to Facebook Pixel for more information\r\n\r\nUsers will be notified of any privacy policy changes:\r\n On our Privacy Policy Page\r\n\r\nUsers are able to change their personal information:\r\n By emailing us\r\n\r\nHow does our site handle do not track signals?\r\nWe honor do not track signals and do not track, plant cookies, or use advertising when a Do Not Track (DNT) browser mechanism is in place.\r\n\r\nDoes our site allow third party behavioral tracking?\r\nIts also important to note that we allow third party behavioral tracking\r\n\r\nCOPPA (Children Online Privacy Protection Act)\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to the collection of personal information from children under 13, the Childrens Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA) puts parents in control. The Federal Trade Commission, the nations consumer protection agency, enforces the COPPA Rule, which spells out what operators of websites and online services must do to protect childrens privacy and safety online.\r\n\r\nWe do not specifically market to children under 13.\r\n\r\nFair Information Practices\r\n\r\nThe Fair Information Practices Principles form the backbone of privacy law in the United States and the concepts they include have played a significant role in the development of data protection laws around the globe. Understanding the Fair Information Practice Principles and how they should be implemented is critical to comply with the various privacy laws that protect personal information.\r\n\r\nIn order to be in line with Fair Information Practices we will take the following responsive action, should a data breach occur:\r\nWe will notify the users via email\r\n Within 7 business days\r\nWe will notify the users via in site notification\r\n Within 7 business days\r\n\r\nWe also agree to the individual redress principle, which requires that individuals have a right to pursue legally enforceable rights against data collectors and processors who fail to adhere to the law. This principle requires not only that individuals have enforceable rights against data users, but also that individuals have recourse to courts or a government agency to investigate and/or prosecute non-compliance by data processors.\r\n\r\nCAN SPAM Act\r\n\r\nThe CAN-SPAM Act is a law that sets the rules for commercial email, establishes requirements for commercial messages, gives recipients the right to have emails stopped from being sent to them, and spells out tough penalties for violations.\r\n\r\nWe collect your email address in order to:\r\n\r\nTo be in accordance with CANSPAM we agree to the following:\r\n\r\nIf at any time you would like to unsubscribe from receiving future emails, you can email us from our contact form and we will promptly remove you from ALL correspondence.\r\n\r\nAll of Codelab Studios paid sample packs &amp; paid sounds are 100% royalty free for personal use only. Contact us for commercial use. Reselling, redistribution and packaging is completely forbidden.\r\n\r\nWebsite Terms of Service\r\n\r\n1.Acceptance of Terms of Service. This is an agreement between Codelab Studios, (Company), the owner and operator of www.Codelab Studios.com (the Site), and you (you or You), a user of the Site. By using the Site you acknowledge and agree to these Terms of Service and the Privacy Policy, which is incorporated by reference. If you choose to not agree with any of these terms, you may not use the Site.\r\n\r\n2.Changes to Terms of Service\r\n\r\n2.1. Right to Change Terms. The Company reserves the right, in its sole discretion, to change these Terms of Service (Updated Terms) from time to time.\r\n\r\n2.2. Notice of Updated Terms. Unless the Company makes a change for legal or administrative reasons, the Company will provide reasonable advance notice before the Updated Terms become effective. You agree that the Company may notify you of the Updated Terms by posting them on the Site.\r\n\r\n2.3. Acceptance of Updated Terms. Your use of the Site after the effective date of the Updated Terms constitutes your agreement to the Updated Terms. You should review these Terms of Service and any Updated Terms before using the Site.\r\n\r\n2.4. Effective Date of Updated Terms. The Updated Terms will be effective as of the time of posting, or such later date as may be specified in the Updated Terms, and will apply to your use of the Site from that point forward.\r\n\r\n3.Use of Site\r\n\r\n3.1. License. During the term of this agreement, the Company grants you a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license to access the Site for your personal and non-commercial use in accordance with the Terms of Service.\r\n\r\n3.2. Intellectual Property Rights. The design, trademarks, service marks, and logos of the Site (Marks), are owned by or licensed to the Company, subject to copyright and other intellectual property rights under United States, foreign laws and international conventions. The Company reserves all rights not expressly granted in and to the Site. You agree to not engage in the use, copying, or distribution of any of the Site other than expressly permitted.\r\n\r\n3.3. User Conduct\r\n\r\n(a)You may not engage in any of the following prohibited activities:\r\n\r\n(i)copying, distributing, or disclosing any part of the Site in any medium, including without limitation by any automated or non-automated scraping,\r\n\r\n(ii)using any automated system, including without limitation robots, spiders, offline readers, etc., to access the Site,\r\n\r\n(iii)transmitting spam, chain letters, or other unsolicited email,\r\n\r\n(iv)attempting to interfere with, compromise the system integrity or security, or decipher any transmissions to or from the servers running the Site,\r\n\r\n(v)taking any action that imposes, or may impose at our sole discretion an unreasonable or disproportionately large load on Site infrastructure,\r\n\r\n(vi)uploading invalid data, viruses, worms, or other software agents through the Site,\r\n\r\n(vii)collecting or harvesting any personally identifiable information, including account names, from the Site,\r\n\r\n(viii)using the Site for any commercial solicitation purposes,\r\n\r\n(ix)impersonating another person or otherwise misrepresenting your affiliation with a person or entity, conducting fraud, hiding or attempting to hide your identity,\r\n\r\n(x)interfering with the proper working of the Site,\r\n\r\n(xi)accessing any content on the Site through any technology or means other than those provided or authorized by the Site, or\r\n\r\n(xii)bypassing the measures we may use to prevent or restrict access to the Site, including without limitation features that prevent or restrict use or copying of any content or enforce limitations on use of the Service or the content therein.\r\n\r\n4.Third Party Content. Through the Site, you will have the ability to access and/or use content provided by third parties. The Company cannot guarantee that such third party content will be free of material you may find objectionable or otherwise. The Company disclaims any responsibility or liability related to your access or use of any third party content.\r\n\r\n10.Privacy. For information about how the Company collects, uses, and shares your information, please review our Privacy Policy. You agree that by using the Site you consent to the collection, use, and sharing (as set forth in the Privacy Policy) of such information, including the transfer of this information to the United States and/or other countries for storage, processing, and use by the Company.\r\n\r\n5.Copyright Policy. The Company respects the intellectual property rights of others and expects users of the Service to do the same. We will respond to notices of alleged copyright infringement that comply with applicable law and are properly provided to us. If you believe that your Content has been copied in a way that constitutes copyright infringement, please provide our copyright agent with the following information in accordance with the Digital Millennium Copyright Act:\r\n\r\n5.1. a physical or electronic signature of the copyright owner or a person authorized to act on their behalf,\r\n\r\n5.2. identification of the copyrighted work claimed to have been infringed,\r\n\r\n5.3. identification of the material that is claimed to be infringing or to be the subject of infringing activity and that is to be removed or access to which is to be disabled, and information reasonably sufficient to permit us to locate the material,\r\n\r\n5.4. your contact information, including your address, telephone number, and an email address,\r\n\r\n5.5. a statement by you that you have a good faith belief that use of the material in the manner complained of is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law, and\r\n\r\n5.6. a statement that the information in the notification is accurate, and, under penalty of perjury, that you are authorized to act on behalf of the copyright owner.\r\n\r\n6.Trademarks. The Company name and logo are trademarks of the Company, and may not be copied, imitated or used, in whole or in part, without the prior written permission of the Company, except in accordance with our brand guidelines. In addition, all page headers, custom graphics, button icons and scripts are service marks, trademarks, and trade dress of the Company, and may not be copied, imitated, or used, in whole or in part, without prior written permission from the Company.\r\n\r\n7.Promotions. Some users may promote competitions, promotions, prize draws and other similar opportunities on the Site (Third Party Competitions). The Company is not the sponsor or promoter of these Third Party Competitions and does not bear any responsibility or liability for the actions or inactions of any third parties who organize, administer or are otherwise involved in any of promotion of these Third Party Competitions. If you wish to participate in any of these Third Party Competitions, you are responsible for reading and ensuring that you understand the applicable rules and any eligibility requirements and are lawfully able to participate in such Third Party Competitions in your country of residence. If you wish to run your own Third Party Competition on the Platform, you are free to do so provided you comply with our Competition Terms.\r\n\r\n8.Termination\r\n\r\n8.1. Termination upon Notice. Either party may terminate this agreement at any time by notifying the other party.\r\n\r\n8.2. Termination by the Company. The Company may terminate or suspend your access to or ability to use the Site immediately, without prior notice or liability, for any reason or no reason, including breach of this agreement. In particular, the Company may immediately terminate or suspend accounts that have been flagged for repeat copyright infringement.\r\n\r\n8.3. Effect of Termination. Upon termination of your access to or ability to use the Site, your right to use or access the Site will immediately cease.\r\n\r\n8.4. Survival of Provisions. This agreements provisions that by their nature should survive termination shall survive termination, including, without limitation, ownership provisions, warranty disclaimers, and limitations of liability. Termination of your access to and use of the Site shall not relieve you of any obligations arising or accruing prior to termination or limit any liability that you otherwise may have to the Company or any third party.\r\n\r\n9.Disclaimers. The Site is provided as is, without any warranties of any kind.To the fullest extent permissible under applicable law, the Company disclaims all such warranties, express or implied, including, but not limited to, warranties of merchantability, fitness for a particular purpose, non-infringement, accuracy, freedom from errors, suitability of content, or availability.\r\n\r\n10.Limitation of Liability. To the fullest extent permitted by applicable law in no event shall the Company be liable for:\r\n\r\n10.1. any direct, special, indirect or consequential damages, or\r\n\r\n10.2. any other damages of any kind, including but not limited to loss of use, loss of profits or loss of data, whether in an action in contract, tort (including but not limited to negligence) or otherwise, arising out of or in any way connected with the use of or inability to use the Site, including without limitation any damages caused by or resulting from reliance by user on any information obtained from Site, or that result from mistakes, omissions, interruptions, deletion of files or email, errors, defects, viruses, delays in operation or transmission or any failure of performance.\r\n\r\n11.Indemnification. You agree to defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Company, its subsidiaries and affiliated companies, and their officers, directors, employees, contractors and agents from and against any and all claims, causes of action, damages, obligations, losses, liabilities, costs or debt, and expenses (including attorneys fees and costs) and all amounts paid in settlement arising from or relating to use of the Site. The Company may assume the exclusive defense and control of any matter for which users have agreed to indemnify the Company and you agrees to assist and cooperate with the Company in the defense or settlement of any such matters.\r\n\r\n12.Arbitration\r\n\r\n12.1. Claim Procedure. For any dispute you have with the Company, you agree to first contact the Company and attempt to resolve the dispute informally. If the Company has not been able to resolve the dispute with you informally, we each agree to resolve any claim, dispute, or controversy (excluding claims for injunctive or other equitable relief) arising out of or in connection with or relating to this agreement by binding arbitration by the American Arbitration Association (AAA) under the Commercial Arbitration Rules and Supplementary Procedures for Consumer Related Disputes then in effect for the AAA, except as provided herein.\r\n\r\n12.2. Arbitration Location. Unless you and the Company agree otherwise, the arbitration will be conducted in the county where you reside.\r\n\r\n12.3. Arbitration Fees. Each party will be responsible for paying any AAA filing, administrative and arbitrator fees in accordance with AAA rules, except that the Company will pay for your reasonable filing, administrative, and arbitrator fees if your claim for damages does not exceed $75,000 and is non-frivolous (as measured by the standards set forth in Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 11(b)).\r\n\r\n12.4. Arbitration Award. The award rendered by the arbitrator shall include costs of arbitration, reasonable attorneys fees and reasonable costs for expert and other witnesses, and any judgment on the award rendered by the arbitrator may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction.\r\n\r\n12.5. Injunctive Relief. Nothing in this Section shall prevent either party from seeking injunctive or other equitable relief from the courts for matters related to data security, intellectual property or unauthorized access to the Service.\r\n\r\n12.6. Class Actions. All claims must be brought in the parties individual capacity, and not as a plaintiff or class member in any purported class or representative proceeding, and, unless we agree otherwise, the arbitrator may not consolidate more than one persons claims.\r\n\r\n12.7. Waiver of Jury Trial. You agree that, by entering into these terms, you and the Company are each waiving the right to a trial by jury or to participate in a class action.\r\n\r\n13.Governing Law. This agreement will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Georgia, without regard to its conflict of laws rules.','Privacy Policy','','inherit','closed','closed','','336-revision-v1','','','2018-02-14 04:57:48','2018-02-14 09:57:48','',336,'http://codelabstudios.com/336-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2017-03-12 19:06:26','2017-03-12 19:06:26','[cs_content][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]How do you try to be really productive at your business only to have a life get in the way multiple times throughout the day?\n\nThis happened to me yesterday and the distractions were at their worst.\n\nHere are Chrome Extensions to help you be more productive in business (or life).\n\nTodobook\n\nNow I was going to suggest a Facebook blocker of course, but like me, many of us use Facebook for business.\n\nIn my case Facebook Ads Manager is where I spend most of my time or checking out what\'s new in the marketing world.\n\nThat\'s why instead of completely blocking Facebook to increase your productivity, simply block the most distracting part.\n\nThe infamous endless newsfeed.\n\nThis little nifty extension will definitely increase your productivity because you won\'t be bombarded by the general useless information in your newsfeed.\n\nOften you find yourself scrolling without even noticing it, those minutes add up over\ntime.\n\nI haven\'t even mentioned the best part, instead of the newsfeed being displayed on your Facebook, you\'re actually presented with a to do list.\n\nThis is how Facebook should be by default I would say.\n\n1Password\nBefore I stress how important this application is, I am in no way to getting paid to say this.\n\n1Password will make you more productive, especially in your business, we will often have a plethora of sites you need to log in to.\n\nInstead of having the same password for everything, we\'re saving your passwords in the chrome Web browser (hint: not safe), you can have 1Password Store everything and only display them to you when you need them.\n\nSavory an example, I want to log into my Facebook ads account, the widget Will show itself in the top right corner of chrome (if keep in toolbar is enabled), and with two clicks you can quickly login.\n\nThis may seem like a simple program, but I guarantee you it is much more than that.\n\nNot only has it save me so much time and increase my security (because you need a master password to access all the passwords), but it just has made my productivity go up immensely across all devices.\n\nOh yeah, forgot to mention it syncs across all your devices securely as well.\n\nWhen I was introduced to this program by my cofounder I couldn\'t believe how useful it actually became in saving me so much time. Easily the best $60 investment I have made in a while.\n\nI highly recommend this program to increase your productivity.\n\n Pocket\n\nThis simple chrome extension packs a powerful punch for productivity.\n\nIf you\'re checking on your competitors, looking at new marketing tactics, we\'re seeing how much a custom website will cost you, you can save all those links in pocket.\n\nPocket is essentially supercharged bookmark bar.\n\nThroughout the workday you\'re going to be tempted with new interesting technologies or information relevant to growing your business.\n\nWhile this seems good, switching gears to focus on that new information will cause you to lose your momentum.\n\nNow multiply that through the many times a day you will be tempted to veer off task, instead just save it in Pocket for later.\n\nThis way you can stay productive while still learning about whatever it is you wanted to view at that moment, only at a later time, across all your devices.\n\nYou can save something on your Mac or Windows, and view it later on your iPhone or android.\n\nStrict Workflow\n\nIf you\'re still having trouble staying productive, you can always try a combination of the Pomodoro technique and temporarily website blocking.\n\nThis is great for you ADHD entrepreneurs out there especially.\n\nThe Pomodoro technique, for those who don\'t know already, is a time management method developed in the 1980s.\n\nEssentially you force yourself to hyperfocus for about 25-30 minutes, then take short 3 to 5 minute breaks.\n\nThink of it as productivity sprints instead of productivity marathons.\n\nThis keeps your brain engaged long enough to complete any broken down task at hand.\n\nYou can also play with the time lengths of course to see what works best for you.\n\nI don\'t know he uses method, but when I do, I noticed a definite surge in productivity and tasks I accomplish.\n\nThe main thing about this method is having the discipline to work within those to time constraints (productivity and rest periods).\n\nBoomerang\n\nOf course I\'m going to mention this one.\n\nWhen used in conjunction with the four hour work week method, this can be quite time saving.\n\nTim Ferris explains how he only checks emails about 2 to 3 times a day in his book, the four hour work weeks[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]test[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][/cs_content]','5 Productive Chrome Extensions for Entreprenuers','','draft','closed','open','','boost-productivity-with-these-5-chrome-extensions','','','2017-03-12 19:06:26','2017-03-12 19:06:26','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=277',0,'post','',0),(352,1,'2017-03-21 17:58:30','2017-03-21 17:58:30','[cs_content][/cs_content]','Cost of a Custom Website','','draft','closed','open','','cost-of-a-custom-website','','','2018-02-14 05:30:43','2018-02-14 10:30:43','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=286',0,'post','',0),(3033,2,'2016-02-03 05:37:48','2016-02-03 05:37:48','<h2>The Social Media Revolution</h2>\n\nThe landscape of Search Engine Optimization (SEO) has began to shift towards social media marketing in the past decade. Social media users have grown exponentially in the past decade, exceeding 1 billion users for Facebook. We\'re using Facebook as a barometer for all social media platforms, but we can safely assume a similar growth trend for other sites such as Twitter, Google+, Pinterest, & LinkedIn.\n\n<img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/facebook-user-by-year-300x181.png\" alt=\"facebook-user-by-year\" width=\"300\" height=\"181\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-3053\" />\n\nWith so many users on social media sites, these platforms have naturally become a source of organic traffic for small businesses. Quality content that was shared can be viewed by many internet surfers who are looking for information in that specific topic.\n\n<h2>The Evolution of Backlinks</h2>\nBacklinks are URL on a website pointing to another web address. They are an especially important element on a webpage because they help direct traffic to your intended location.\n\nThe strategy for generating organic traffic before Google updated their search algorithm in the Google Panda update was to create many articles with links pointing back to your site. These articles would contain similar content that had slight wording changes to avoid penalty for having duplicate content.\n\nThese content would then be submitted to article directoy listings such as Squidoo and Ezinearticles. Article directory submissions were the way to rank your site on the first page of Google, but those days are bygone.\n\n<h2>Shift to Social Media</h2>\nIn our present digital life, social media usage takes up a significant portion of our time. Users are constantly looking for interesting articles and relevant information on these platforms. If you make yourself available on these avenues, these traffic could convert in to sales and profit.\n\nSocial media marketing is so prevalent because they provide a low cost alternative to paid advertising. Not only that, your social media posts are permanent, and don\'t expire like Pay Per Click (PPC) or Pay Per View (PPV) models to. That means more low cost exposure for small businesses. It could be more cost effective to create weekly updates to Facebook & Twitter than to pay for advertising.\n\n<h2>What It Means for SEO</h2>\nA lot of people say SEO is gone or dead, but that is not the case. It just means there are less tricks you can do to rank sub-quality content. Google\'s goal is to make the ultimate algorithm that accurate accesses a content\'s quality, and appropriately rank it. Ultimately, content is and always will be king.','The Shift to Social Media Marketing','','draft','closed','open','','the-shift-to-social-media-marketing','','','2016-02-03 05:37:48','2016-02-03 05:37:48','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3033',0,'post','',0),(3096,2,'2016-03-03 22:01:29','2016-03-03 22:01:29','No two businesses are created equal, and neither should their advertising strategy be. Online advertising is complicated, specifically when it comes to investing in an appropriate strategy. Whether youre considering Pay Per View (PPV), Pay Per Click (PPC), or Affiliate Advertising, it literally pays to know what youre doing.\r\n\r\nSo which strategy is right for you, what are the differences between each, and what are their pros and cons?\r\n<h2>What is Pay Per View (PPV) Advertising?</h2>\r\nPPV stands for Pay Per View and it charges advertisers each time their page or ad is viewed. It is an advertising model based on ad impressions users actually view.\r\n\r\n<em>Pros</em>: PPV provides more flexibility, a greater return on investment, and doesnt require keywords to be effective.\r\n\r\n<em>Cons</em>: Fewer advertisers, frequent pop-up ads, possible impression fraud on the account of advertisers.\r\n\r\n<em>When to use it:</em> If your website isnt suitable for Adsense, then Pay Per View Advertising may be an ideal strategy for your company.\r\n<h2>What is <strong>Pay Per Click (PPC</strong>) <strong>Advertising</strong>?</h2>\r\nPPC, or Pay Per Click, advertising only charges you when someone clicks on the ads on your website, forum or blog. You never pay if someone visits your website without clicking on your ads.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Pros</em></strong>: User-friendly, easy to activate via AdWords, consistent earnings, streamlined management\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Cons</em></strong>: Limited earnings, is something you could do on your own without paying high advertising fees\r\n\r\n<strong><em>When to use it</em></strong>: If you have a small, up-in-coming website that can later be converted to Pay Per View advertising.\r\n<h2>What is <strong>Affiliate Advertising</strong>?</h2>\r\nAffiliate advertising targets bloggers who are looking for a way to generate revenue from their blog. Advertisers pay to promote their products through select websites, and in return enjoy increased traffic.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Pros</em></strong>: Affordability, potential to increase your list of customers and grow your audience\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Cons</em></strong>: Time sensitive, little to no real results.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>When to use it</em></strong>: If youre just starting out and trying to gain brand awareness.\r\n<h2>PPV and PPC Similarities and Differences</h2>\r\nPPV and PPC are primarily different in the method through which you are charged. PPC costs you when a user clicks on your ads, PPV costs only when viewers come to your website.\r\n\r\nPPV takes precedence over PPC in regards to awareness. Users can see your landing page or website via a pop-up ad, which often leads to increased traffic. Additionally, the price rate for PPV is more affordable, somewhere between $0.004 and $0.015 per view.\r\n\r\nPPC offers extensive resources to advertisers. This strategy also makes it possible to display your ads on search results right in front of your audience in relation to their search keywords. They also give advertisers greater control over their message, and narrow ads based on geography, culture, and demographics.\r\n\r\n<strong>Summary</strong>:\r\n\r\nSelecting the correct advertising method is critical to your success as an online business. Keep this information front and center to make an educated decision.','Pay Per Click (PPC) vs Pay Per View (PPV) Advertising','','publish','closed','open','','pay-per-click-ppc-vs-pay-per-view-ppc-advertising-when-to-use-each','','','2018-02-14 05:32:34','2018-02-14 10:32:34','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3096',0,'post','',0),(3104,2,'2016-03-03 22:54:05','2016-03-03 22:54:05','We live in a modern digital age with access to very power mobile devices, which are much more powerful than computers of the past.Processors are becoming more powerful &amp; more battery-efficient, allowing complex tasks to be done over an extended period of time.Our dependence on technology almost makes it mandatory for us to have a device at all times. In fact, we have reached a new mobile age where users of mobile devices are surpassing that of desktop uses.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3344 size-full\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Mobile-stats-vs-desktop-users-global-550x405.png\" alt=\"Mobile Stats Vs. Desktop Use\" width=\"550\" height=\"405\" />\n<h2>What makes a site mobile-friendly and responsive</h2>\nThe design of a website is edited by adding CSS code. The Cascading Style Sheet code targets HTML elements and adds colors, changes font sizes, adds padding &amp; margin, and sets box widths and heights. A combination of these different codes determine how a size will look when rendered by the browser.\n\nLet\'s say you have a box that you set to 960px, which is the standard width of a web page (although a web outdated now that screen sizes are much larger), it will render as 960px. If you set the width to 100% however, it will always be full width no matter what your screen size is. Mobile-friendly design uses such technique to make sure all content will fit to the screen. on a mobile screen of 480px, the 960px will overflow to the sides, while a 100% width will just be 480px.\n<h2>Mobilegedoon strikes the internet on April 21st, 2015</h2>\nGoogle is no doubt the largest search engine in the world, and to rank higher on its Seearch Engine Results Page (SERP), we should take note of its ranking algorithm. Just not too long ago, Google released a ranking algorithm so significant that it shook up the internet with terms such as \"Mobilegeddon\", \"Mobilepocalysts\", \"Mopocalypse\", or \"Mobocalypse\".\n\nThis new update would take into account a site\'s \"mobile friendliness\" into Google\'s ranking. Remember that time when you open up a web page, and the text were so tiny that you had to two-finger pinch zoom in to read anything? You probably had to rotate your phone to landscape mode just to give your content more real estate. You mostly like also had to scroll left to right just to read all the content. A site like that would definitely NOT be responsive, and Google did this update to push towards better user experience on phones.\n<h2>The standardized mobile friendly test</h2>\nGoogle also rolled out its standardized test for your website, called the<a href=\"https://www.google.com/webmasters/tools/mobile-friendly/\" target=\"_blank\">Mobile Friendly Test</a>. The test is pretty simple, you just type your URl into the input field, then click Analyze. After a minute or so, Google will tell you whether your site is mobile friendly or not. I did a quick test for https://codelabstudios.dev and the results are shown below:\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3106 size-full\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Screenshot-2016-03-03-14.53.55.png\" alt=\"google mobile friendly test\" width=\"1453\" height=\"976\" />\n\n&nbsp;\n<h2>The algorithm in more detail</h2>\nSo your mobile site will have an advantage over other non-mobile sites when ranking on Google\'s search results page. The weight of this mobile-friendly factor in comparison to the hundreds of other factors Google uses to determine the over ranking is unknown however. Google doesn\'t release details like this, but all we know is that there is some advantage if your site passes the test.\n\nOne last important thing to note, the mobile-friendly advantage only applies to searches made on mobile devices. So if you were to make a search query on your laptop, then the mobile-friendly factor wouldn\'t apply to the ranking of the sites. Even though it doesn\'t affect desktop searches, I would say a majority of searches come from smart phones these days, so it would make sense to make your sites responsive.\n<h2>Website redesigns to the rescue</h2>\nNon-mobile friendly sites are a problem mostly with old sites. Newerwebsites created around 2010\'s or later are most responsive out of the box. Many pre-made Wordpress, Drupal, Magento, Shopify themes are already responsive to begin with. With older sites, you could simply add CSS code to override the current design and made it mobile friendly. We do offer such services at Codelab Studios for a small fee, so please contact us for more information.\n\n&nbsp;','The importance of making all your web pages mobile friendly','','draft','closed','open','','the-importance-of-making-all-your-web-pages-mobile-friendly','','','2016-03-03 22:54:05','2016-03-03 22:54:05','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3104',0,'post','',0),(3320,2,'2016-04-09 04:55:49','2016-04-09 04:55:49','Advertising on the internet is broken down into two major types, searchand display. Search results deal with what people type into the search engine when looking for information. These specific keywords determine the search results people get, as well as the type of <strong>search ads</strong> they will receive. When you enter a website and you see advertising on the sidebar, this is the <strong>display ads</strong>.\n<h2>Google AdWords is Google\'s advertising on the search network</h2>\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3321 size-full\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Screenshot-2016-04-08-21.03.24.png\" alt=\"Screenshot 2016-04-08 21.03.24\" width=\"826\" height=\"501\" />\n\nSay for example you Google\'d \'Web Design Firms in Los Angeles\', the ad results will show up in the search results if those keywords are been bid on. The price of the ad is determined by a system where the highest bidder wins the ad.\n<h2>Google AdSense is Google\'s advertising on the displaynetwork</h2>\nOnce you are inside a website, you may see advertising on the sidebar or header area. These advertisements are considered to be on the display network. More often than not, the ad you\'re seeing would be AdSense.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-3322 size-full\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/Screenshot-2016-04-08-21.15.34.png\" alt=\"Google AdSense Example\" width=\"1274\" height=\"448\" />\n<h2>When To Use the Display Network</h2>\nWhen you are browsing a website, say YouTube, and you see an advertisement for a automobile, you wouldn\'t necessarily be buying a car at the moment. But it does set you up for the future with its branding and product image. Traditional broadcasting networks are also examples of the display network, they advertise products or services that you may not be interested in at the moment, but rather something you might need in the future. This plays to advertising\'s subconscious aspect, where the branding affects the buyers decision.\n\nPeople seeing ads in the display network are in the early phase of the conversion cycle. They are just beginning to learn about your business, or are being reminded again of your service.If you are trying to make people see your product in a certain way, or are trying to set a brand image for your business, then the display network would be your choice.\n<h2>When To Use the Search Network</h2>\nPeople who are typing in search keywords are already showing some interest in the product.They are at a later point in the conversion cycle. Searching for \"Web Design Agencies in Los Angeles\", you might want a new website for your business, or learn more about what the cost would be. People at this phase are more likely to start spending money, and it is where profits can be made.\n\nA user could end up choosing your business over competitors because your search results were the first they see. In essence, you are paying money to be on the number one spot on Google. Instead of doing the laborious task of organic SEO and landing yourself on the first page, you simply pay Google through AdWords and get yourself a spot there.\n\nWhile SEO definitely could help, there is still a chance for you to be seen on the first spot on Google through advertising on the search network.\n<h2>Why Not Use All The Strategies</h2>\nIn an ideal world, you would advertise on both the search and display network. Your display network ads will make customers aware of your business, then the next time they search for services your businesses offer, they\'ll give you a consideration having seen you previously.\n\nFor businesses starting out, the first step is for brand recognition. So display advertising might be the better choice. After the audience gets you know a little better, start putting more money in search advertising and try to convert those into sales. Don\'t forget to work on your organic SEO though!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','How Marketing Strategies Differ on the Search Network vs the Display Network','','draft','closed','open','','search-network-vs-display-network-marketing','','','2016-04-09 04:55:49','2016-04-09 04:55:49','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3320',0,'post','',0),(3336,2,'2016-04-09 06:33:57','2016-04-09 06:33:57','[cs_content][cs_section parallax=\"false\" separator_top_type=\"none\" separator_top_height=\"50px\" separator_top_angle_point=\"50\" separator_bottom_type=\"none\" separator_bottom_height=\"50px\" separator_bottom_angle_point=\"50\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]<h2>What Is Inbound Marketing?</h2>\n\n<strong>Inbound marketing</strong> involves customers or prospects coming to you. This can be from them visiting your website, contacting you for services, calling in, etc.\n\nThis is the often more sought after form of marketing because\n\nInstead of having salesperson calling clients, the clients are the ones reaching out to the business. And by what mysterious voodoo magic can this be achieved you might ask. The answer is through <strong>content marketing</strong>.\n\nIn other words, inbound marketing is just a big umbrella term for any type of marketing that brings the attention of an audience. In contrast to outbound marketing, where the business actively seeks out to the audience, inbound marketing is the other way around.[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]The field of digital marketing haswitnessed a huge growth as social media became ubiquitous in our modern age. With so many marketing strategies and terminologies, it can be confusing sometimes to even people within the industry. Inbounding marketing and content marketing are two of those terms that are used interchangeably, despite minute nuances.[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]<h2>What Is ContentMarketing?</h2>\n\nContent marketing is one of those strategies businesses employ to gain the attention of potential customers. By producing relevant and enticing content, users will subscribe to newsletter and keep updated with future updates. Not only is this strategy more authentic then cold calling clients, it provides greater long term value for your customer.[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]<h2>Other Types Inbound Marketing</h2>\n\nIn other words, content marketing is a subset of inbound marketing. There are other forms of inbound marketing, as content marketing is not the only strategy.\n\n<h3>Social Media</h3>\n\nSocial media is another form on inbound marketing. By deciding whatinformation to share, you choose to connect with a certain type of audience. You can shape your online image by carefully showing interest in certain subjects. You may say that isn\'t genuine or authentic, but that is the gist of social media. You decide what to share to the world to show that you are cool.\n\n<h3>SEO</h3>\n\nSEO is very similar to content marketing. Both you are sharing useful content to draw the users in. SEO is strictly just the text on your web page, and not any additional material you may provide on your site. You may have an e-book or tutorials on a subject, but that wouldn\'t be considered SEO because a search engine can\'t index the information contained within a video, or a PDF.\n\n<h3>PPC</h3>\n\nThere has been some debate about whetherPPC is inbound or outbound marketing. Since traditional advertising is considered outbound marketing, some people are saying PPC is advertising as well, and should be considered outbound. However, some people argue that since PPC links are related to the keywords you type in, the user was already actively looking for the information. In either case, PPC is another method you can draw users into your site.\n[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][/cs_content]','Inbound Marketing Vs. Content Marketing','','draft','closed','open','','inbound-marketing-vs-content-marketing','','','2016-04-09 06:33:57','2016-04-09 06:33:57','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3336',0,'post','',0),(3413,2,'2016-04-13 03:02:16','2016-04-13 03:02:16','When the dot-com boom hit around 2000, where the internet became more readily available and easier to access, the number of websites started to grow exponential. Even to this day, the growth is still in its exponential phase, currently with about 644 million active websites. As platforms and frameworks become more widespread, even more websites continue to flood the internet. Wordpress, which began as a blogging platform, has evolved to the point where it can functionas a regular website. Some web applications are even ran on Wordpress. With so many different types of sites, how do we categorize each type?\n<h2>Landing Page</h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-3402 size-medium\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/landing-page-rocket-300x207.jpg\" alt=\"Landing Page Rocket\" width=\"300\" height=\"207\" />A landing page is designed to get a user to carry out an action, whether it\'stopurchase a product or subscribe to the newsletter.Since you don\'t want to distract the user with too many options, a landing page will usually only contain 1 page &amp; few buttons. Catchy headlines and promising descriptions are common to a landing page, in order to draw their attentions and interests. Such pages are the life and blood of online businesses, as it is the final step a user performs before spending money. If you are selling products or services, be sure to have a simple and clean landing page to help you with conversion.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2>Content Website</h2>\nMost websites are considered content websites. Such siteusually contains multiple pages like the Homepage, About Us, Products, Services, Contact. Content websites are good for personal portfolios including artists, musicians,web freelancers, photographers, and such. Local small businesses can also have a website to show customers who they are and what they do. A website is extremely versatile as you can add a Blog page to it as well. A landing page could also be built in on one of the pages (while you would want to hide some navigation items to avoid distracting the users from the end goal). Websites will cost more than a landing page because of the extra pages, but having a website for any small business is highly recommended in our modern age.\n<h2>E-Commerce</h2>\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-3290 alignleft\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ecommerce-shopping-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"E-Commerce Business\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />\n\nAs you can tell from the name, e-commerce site are sites that are capable of handling purchases and payments. You generally have a list of products with buttons to add to your shopping cart, and a checkout button that takes you to the payment page. These sites start with pre-made platforms, and are customized to suit the clients needs. Common platforms include Shopify, Magento, and WooCommerce. There\'s always an admin backend for sales and payment management. After a developer sets the site up, you don\'t have to deal with any code when using the admin panel. In order to take payments securely, the site requires an SSL certificate. These certificates provide better data encryption and hides it from potentialhackers.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2>Webapps</h2>\nWebapps are apps for the web. They do more than just showing content or blogs. Webapps help you perform tasks and automate things.There are services that provide email analytics like email open rates, send success rates, and user agents information. Sites like Postmark &amp; Sendgrid provide these services when you sign up to their site. These sites are much more complicated and require a team of developers to create. They are essential apps, the only difference is that you access them on a browser instead of on your phone or tablet.\n\nIf you are a small business owner, you\'llwant a content website as a business front for the internet. Here you can provide some information on what products or services you provide. A contact page will provide an easy to use email form for users with questions. If you happen to have products, you\'ll want this website to have e-commerce capabilities. You may create a separate site for shopping, or just make your e-commerce site your content website as well. Once you have your primary site set up, you can create ad campaigns with landing pages set up to help with conversion rates. You generally won\'t need a webapp unless your company is providing software as a service or SAAS.','What are the Major Types and Categories of Websites?','','draft','closed','open','','different-types-websites','','','2016-04-13 03:02:16','2016-04-13 03:02:16','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3413',0,'post','',0),(3446,2,'2016-07-18 18:08:56','2016-07-18 18:08:56','<h2>What is traditional marketing?</h2>\n<strong>Traditional marketing </strong>incorporates several forms of both advertising and marketing. Most well-known tactics include advertisements that most of us see and hear every single day. These include:\n<ul>\n	<li>Print</li>\n	<li>Broadcasting</li>\n	<li>Telephone (cold-calling)</li>\n	<li>Direct Mail Advertisements</li>\n</ul>\nPrint marketing is the most familiar and the oldest form of marketing. Beginning with traditional newspaper ads, print advertisements continue to find their way in front of us even some 150 years after their invention.\n\nBroadcast ads include radio advertisements and television commercials. Specialized forms of broadcast ads include movie theater ads.\n\n<strong>Telephone marketing</strong>or telemarketingis another popular form of advertisement. While not the most popular, it continues to make an impact.\n\nDirect mail advertisements include fliers, postcards, letters or any other material that is directly mailed to potential consumers.\n<h2>What is digital marketing?</h2>\n<strong>Digital marketing is</strong> the new wave of advertising. It too is an umbrella term defined by the medium through which marketers push either digital technologies or offline products that can easily be marketed online.\n\nExamples of <strong>digital marketing</strong> include websites, social networking sites, content marketing, video marketing, Google ads, and banner ads.\n\nDigital marketing enables marketers to monitor the effectiveness of their ads, what is being viewed most, sales conversion, what content is working and what isnt all with the click of a mouse.\n<h2>Cost for traditional marketing vs digital marketing</h2>\n<strong>Traditional marketing</strong> continues to be a major player in consumer advertising. Despite this, many startups struggle with the costs associated with the strategy. For example, to take out a full page spread ad in a magazine (a common form of traditional advertising) youre looking at anywhere from $5,000-$10,000 and in some cases even more than that. A broadcast ad might cost $150, but your reach isnt likely to be as stunning.\n\n<strong>Digital marketing</strong> is the new kid on the block, and highly respected by a large and small companies alike. The costs for <strong>online marketing</strong> vary greatly. For example, you can sign-up for social media campaigns that cost around $75 a month to reach thousands of people. Additionally, you could hire an SEO firm to market your website and do all the hard work for you and pay around $1,500 a month for full-service digital marketing. Youll reach hundreds of thousandspossibly millionsof consumers and have a better chance of converting them as well.\n<h3>Content distribution and audience outreach</h3>\nContent distribution is based on how many people you can reach with a particular form of advertising. If youre using <strong>traditional marketing</strong> methods, your reach is either based on A) your ability to physically distribute ads and filers to the right audience or B) the reach of the form of media you are using. Print, broadcasting, and even television viewing to some extent, have greatly reduced over the past decade. Audiences are turning to digital media for content.\n\n<strong>Digital marketing</strong> has a different outlook. If you spend around $75 for social media ads, you can reach at least 2,000 people quickly. Compare that with traditional marketing, and you can expect to pay a minimum of $150 for the same reach.\n<h3>Conversion rate and effectiveness</h3>\n<strong>Digital marketing</strong> outpaces <strong>traditional marketing</strong> within conversion rates and overall effectiveness. An Inbound Report conducted by HubPages, noted that 54% more leads are generated by inbound tactics (digital marketing) than by traditional paid advertising. Content marketing (or <strong>online marketing</strong>) is also shown to generate 3 times more leads as traditional marketing methods, and the kicker is it costs upwards of 62% less.','Traditional Marketing vs. Digital Marketing','','draft','closed','open','','traditional-marketing-vs-digital-marketing','','','2016-07-18 18:08:56','2016-07-18 18:08:56','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3446',0,'post','',0),(3730,1,'2017-04-15 21:35:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','[cs_content][cs_section bg_color=\"hsl(182, 55%, 58%)\" parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text class=\"cs-ta-center\"]<h1>6 Ways to Grow your Email List by 3x</h1>\n[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column id=\"intro\" fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 20px 50px 0px;\"][cs_text class=\"cs-ta-center\"]<span id=\"intro\">Learn marketing tactics to increase the amount of potential customers signing up to join your email list.</span>[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 20px 10% 45px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][x_line style=\"border-top-color: hsl(0, 0%, 100%);border-top-width: 1px;\"][x_custom_headline level=\"h2\" looks_like=\"h3\" accent=\"false\"]Intro[/x_custom_headline][cs_text class=\"cs-ta-left\"]Hey business owners today I\'m going to talk about 5 ways that you can increase the amount of people joining your email list.\n\nBefore we jump into the tips, I want to talk about why it is the fourth builder of you before we jump into the tips, I want to talk about why it is important to be building your email list everyday\n\nWhy is email important for my business?\n\nHaving someone who might be interested in your services give you your email, is now more valuable than ever. I would rather have 1000 emails of potential prospects, than 5000 home addresses of the same prospects to send physical mail to.\n\nTactic #1\nOffer a discount on your services\n\nIf you were in the low ticket industry, offering a discount on your products or even in some cases a free product, is a great way to get your customers to visit your website with an ad or opt in the email so that you can target them later.\n\nIf you\'re hoping that people will care to opt into your newsletter without you offering anything additional to that, you\'re going to be sadly mistaken these days.\n\nFrom AB test we\'ve run where we had email often forms offering nothing other than just updates and tips compared to opt in form is offering things such as a free download of some digital content, we saw often rates jumped by at least 5x.\n\nThis percentage increase varies depending on the industry, but overall giving something valuable to the consumer in exchange for them giving you their email, produces significantly more opt ins.\n\nTactic #2\nHost an old-fashioned giveaway\n\nWhen you see those ads on Facebook giving away free things, (usually electronics), take a second to look at that next time. You\'re going to fine they want something in return, usually it\'s an email, share, or like.\n\nNow let\'s take it a step further rather than giving away just a free iPhone or something meaningless like that. Give away something that your ideal customers would want.\n\nYou might need to get a little creative.\n\nIf you\'re in the automotive industry, give away a new set of tires. If you\'re in the home remodeling space, give away a brand-new bathroom remodel. If you were in the restaurant industry (which is a little easier because who doesn\'t like to eat), offer a free dinner to one lucky winner.\n\nDepending on if you do your marketing right, this can generate hundreds if not thousands of people that would be interested in your product or service. You can quickly see how that would easily cover the cost of the prize to the winner.\n\n\nTactic #3\n include a downloadable PDF of whatever topic it is your blogging about\n\nThis one works very well too, especially if you\'re in the high ticket industry.\n\nLet\'s say you do plumbing and HVAC.\n\nA great example of this would be a 15 point checklist of things you can do as a homeowner to prevent damage to your plumbing and HVAC system.\n\nSome of you might be thinking right now, \"But why would I tell my potential customers how not to need me?\".\n\nEasy.\n\nGuess who\'s going to be top of mind when something does go wrong with their plumbing or HVAC?\n\nJoe Schmo\'s Plumbing on Yelp?\n\nOr you, the person who gave them a free resource without asking for anything but an email, and have been periodically providing free preventative care value to them via email?\n\nThe goal is to make yourself be the person I think about when they might need your services.\n\n\nTactic #3\nHost a giveaway\n\n Regardless of your industry, I\'m sure there is something that you can find valuable to your potential customers to give away for free. Giveaways are not a thing of the past, they have worked extremely well for some of our clients.\n\nLet\'s say you\'re in the home inspection industry. You could be giving away a free home inspection to one person who enters.\n\nThe requirements\nMake sure that the competition is social, social proof will help out immensely in getting even more people to join a giveaway. The most common form of entering a game wa make sure that the competition is social, social proof will help out immensely in getting even more people to join a giveaway. The most common form of entering a giveaway,  is by asking your potential customers to Upton with their email address.\n\nThe less hurdles you make your audience jump through, and the more[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][/cs_content]','6 Tips to Build Your Email List','','draft','closed','open','','how-to-build-email-list','','','2017-04-15 21:35:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3730',0,'post','',0),(3749,1,'2017-04-17 19:41:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00','[cs_content][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 45px 0px 35px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][x_image type=\"none\" src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/04/emails.jpg\" alt=\"\" link=\"false\" href=\"#\" title=\"\" target=\"\" info=\"none\" info_place=\"top\" info_trigger=\"hover\" info_content=\"\"][cs_text]In modern business, maintaining a strong relationship with your clients has become a key part of business growth.\n</br>Even though many aspects of businesses are becoming automated, customer relations are one thing which cant be automated without being easily noticeable.\n\nWithin minutes of a customer alerting you of their unhappiness towards your service, they can quickly publish their (albeit unwanted) opinion to social media and tarnish the reputation which youve carefully built up.\n\n<a href=\"\">Because of this, if you havent done so already, then you should prioritise the relationships which you have with your customers.\n[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 0px 0px 45px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text class=\"cs-ta-center\"]<span class=\"quote\">Do what you do so well that they will want to see it again and bring their friends.  <strong>Walt Disney</strong></span>[/cs_text][cs_text]<span class=\"popout\">Hey! This is the <a href=\"#\">.popout</a> class! Use it wisely.</span> [/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: 0px 0px 45px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]With more and more businesses arising every day, every industrys competition is growing and because of this, a high-standard of customer relations is expected. Businesses who dont prioritise this are simply expected to fail; its true, if you dont prioritise customer relations then you will fail as a business.\n[/cs_text][cs_text class=\"cs-ta-center\"]Here are some statistics from 2012 to back up this claim:[/cs_text][cs_text]<hr />\n<ul>\n<li>A measly 37% of businesses received the ratings Excellent and Good for their customer relations. On the other hand, 63% of businesses received either Okay, Poor, or Very Poor ratings for their customer relations.</li>\n<hr />\n<li>Following a poor experience, 89% took to a businesses competitors instead.</li>\n<hr />\n<li> 60% of customers would rather pay more money for good customer relations, opposed to having a cheap service with a poor customer experience.</li>\n<hr />\n<li>On average, businesses who lost a customer to one of their competitors lost $289 per lost customer.</li>\n</ul>[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][cs_section parallax=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px;padding: px 0px 45px;\"][cs_row inner_container=\"true\" marginless_columns=\"false\" style=\"margin: 0px auto;padding: 0px;\"][cs_column fade=\"false\" fade_animation=\"in\" fade_animation_offset=\"45px\" fade_duration=\"750\" type=\"1/1\" style=\"padding: 0px;\"][cs_text]These statistics speak for themselves and go to show that if you dont already do so, then its time to prioritise customer relations and make sure that your customers have the best experience possible.\nWith that, below we have put together 6 of the best ways to make customers love your business as well as increase the number of customers that you receive.\n#1  Interact With Your Customers\nAs we mentioned above, businesses are beginning to be automated and so they are missing out on the personal level of their service. Although automation can be helpful, theres one thing that it wont help you with. Interacting with your customers.\nActually interacting with your customers rather than just providing them with a service is important as it goes to show that you genuinely care about providing a top-notch service and lets face it, if you dont interact with your customers then youre going to lose potential clients and fail as a business.\nOn top of that, dont talk to them like a robot. Youre not talking to the press or publishing a scientific study, so speak to them as if they were in front of you and you are having a conversation. Make them feel like you care about their needs and what theyre looking for in a business, and youll undoubtedly have a long-time customer.\n#2  Listen to Your Customers\nA lot of businesses nowadays have become egotistical and disregard customer feedback due to the fact that it isnt a professional opinion. Although this is true, customer feedback can help you to improve your everyday business and find out what it was that your customers liked about the service which you provide, as well as the things they didnt like.\nThere are a few different ways to get feedback from customers youve dealt with, such as:\n	Social media pages\n	Asking potential customers through relevant communities\n	Simply asking customers who youve worked with in the past\n	Emailing customers which a survey which is relevant to the service that you provided them with\nThese are just a few of the most effective ways to gather helpful feedback to improve your service overall, and ultimately increase your customer count.\n#3  Provide Transparency\nCustomers want to know everything about your business and they dont want to jump through hoops just to find out details about you that they should otherwise know. Because of that, transparency is something which is expected from businesses nowadays. This is especially important for online businesses.\nWhat does it mean for a business to be transparent?\n	Transparency is when you dont avoid your customers.\n	Transparency is when you welcome any feedback which you receive from your customers.\n	Transparency is when you and your employees dont have to alter your personalities at work.\n	Transparency is when you dont have anything to hide.\nGiven that there are still businesses out there who dont provide transparency, by incorporating it into your business and having nothing to hide, youre giving yourself a leg up over your competitors.\n#4  Keep Your Word\nContinuing up on the previous point, keeping your word and not letting your customer down helps to build trust between you and your customers. If you make promises which you yourself are unsure about, or which you know you cant keep, then your customers will lose trust in you and will know that you arent a reliable business to deal with.\nYour word is your bond.  Melvyn Douglas\nIf you arent able to keep a promise that you are going to make, cut yourself off and dont make that promise. If you arent able to meet your customers deadline, let them know before its too late.\nBe comfortable with the work that you take on, dont take on more work than you or your business is not capable of completing in the timespan which is provided, and complete it to your best standard. By doing this your customers will see you as a reliable business who they can trust and will return to you in the future.\n#5  Relax and Respect\nAround 1 in every 3 customers have said that they have experienced rude customer service a minimum of once a month. Following this, roughly 58-percent of these people will tell their friends about this rude experience.\nWord of mouth has always been, and will also be, an effective way of marketing. However, there is such as a thing as bad word of mouth and this is a prime example of it. If you find that your employees are rude or that you could be more pleasant when dealing with customers, its in your best interests to deal with it effectively.\nEvery business has customers who arent the easiest to work with although this is the sort of thing that you have to have patience for, relax, and deal with appropriately. If you relax and come to an outcome which suits both you and the problematic customer, youll both leave somewhat satisfied.\nBy having respect for your customers and dealing with the issues that they have, theyll provide you with good word of mouth.\n#6  Be a Pleasure to Work With\nThe last thing that were going to discuss is your attitude. Always have a positive attitude when it comes to your business and dont let your personal life get involved with your work. This can cause your business to take a hit if your anger is misdirected, and this is often not something which you can recover from easily.\nIf you are in need of more details from a customer to get started on the service you are providing, always say Please. When they get back to you or compliment the work which youve done for them, always say Thank You. These may seem like basic manners although they can really go a long way.\nAppreciate your customers and theyll appreciate you.\n[/cs_text][/cs_column][/cs_row][/cs_section][/cs_content]','6 Ways to Win Customers to Your Business','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2017-04-17 19:41:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3749',0,'post','',0),(3987,1,'2017-05-21 01:06:01','2017-05-21 01:06:01','If you run a business, you need to be using the best tools to compete in 2017.\r\n\r\nWe\'ve all spent a <strong>ton</strong> of time digging through various web apps, tools, and software so I figured let\'s put and end to that right now and show you the best ones. ?\r\n\r\nIf you\'re an entrepreneur or CEO, here\'s the best marketing <strong>Tools and Web Apps</strong> that you should be using.\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"popout\">Want a free custom marketing plan? - <a href=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/services/#contact\">Just click here.</a></span></blockquote>\r\nI\'m not getting paid by the companies for recommending these - you may notice the <strong>lack of</strong> affiliate links..\r\n\r\nThis is a collection of my personal unbiased favorites coupled with other sources (<a href=\"https://www.designcue.io/bootstrap-tools\">Bootstrap Tools</a>, word of mouth,<a href=\"http://startupstash.com/\">Startup Stash</a>, etc).\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Email Outreach</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/08/MixMax.png\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://mixmax.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">MixMax</a></span>\r\nAt first, I wasn\'t sold on MixMax. After trying out a few competitors, I came running back into their arms.</span></blockquote>\r\nI recently \"un-churned\" back about two months ago and.... just <strong>wow.</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you\'re like me, you\'re big on gathering data to conduct A/B tests and optimize everything more, including email scripts.\r\n\r\n<strong>MixMax is the best software for doing just this.</strong>\r\n\r\nThey pricing can get pretty hefty if you\'re on a budget but they have a nice discount for buying it before you trial ends, <strong>around $20/month.</strong>\r\n\r\nI\'ve found this to be WELL worth it. The email scheduling is like no other, and here\'s the biggest reason for my switch:\r\n\r\n<strong>After testing multiple email outreach softwares, I\'ve found that MixMax actually has <u>some of the highest deliverability rates</u></strong>.\r\n\r\nThis was a very big factor for using them. I cross-tested about 3 competitors against an email spam test to see if it would ever hit the inbox - <strong>MixMax</strong> won by a landslide.\r\n\r\nI don\'t understand the technical aspect as to why their emails get through more but who cares, if I\'m spending time reaching out to people, the <strong>LAST</strong> thing I want is to hit the spam folder.\r\n\r\nFor this reason, they\'re my new favorite.\r\n\r\nPlus their sequences are great for sending one-off emails, it automatically adds that email to the data in that sequence, meaning you don\'t have to constantly keep doing everything in spreadsheets. It still keeps the open data for that specific sequence.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://vocus.io/logo-icon.svg\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://vocus.io\" rel=\"nofollow\">Vocus.io</a></span>\r\nVocus allows you to send outreach email in bulk and has an auto-follow up feature with customizable email sequences. Also the interface is sexy.</span></blockquote>\r\nIf you\'re thinking this is just another email tracking chrome extension well..\r\n\r\n<strong>You\'re right, sort of.</strong>\r\n\r\nOf course you have your standard open &amp; click tracking but it really makes Vocus shine is it\'s <strong>Mail Merge</strong> feature.\r\n\r\nOut of all the email tracking &amp; sequencers I\'ve found, this one has the best interface hands down and is the least buggy.\r\n\r\n<strong>BASICALLY you can send out emails, track when they\'re opened / clicked, and send an auto-follow up reply if the email wasn\'t replied to within a set time.</strong>.\r\n\r\nA very powerful tool for cold-outreach emails or staying on top of potential clients.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Email Marketing</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/05/MailChimp.png\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://mailchimp.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">MailChimp</a></span>\r\nThe undefeated primate king in email marketing. They have nearly two decade\'s worth of polishing and refining to their bulk email platform.</span></blockquote>\r\nIf you\'re going to go big, obviously go with MailChimp.\r\n\r\nTheir customer support, interface, metrics, features and overall email platform is the best.\r\n\r\nThe price point on MailChimp is a bit higher than it\'s competitors but there\'s good reason.\r\n\r\nThey easily walk circles around competitors like SendinBlue &amp; Constant Contact.\r\n\r\n<strong>If you have the budget, go with MailChimp. You get free emailing to your first 2,000 subscribers free as well.</strong> Hard to argue with that.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://emailoctopus.com/bundles/emailoctopuswebsite/images/logo.svg\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://emailoctopus.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Email Octopus</a></span>\r\nMass email marketing for wayy less. It uses Amazon SES and even has email automation built in (email drip campaigns &amp; automated replies).</span></blockquote>\r\nYes.. I know, \"WAIT- But what about MailChimp?!\"\r\n\r\nWell, you probably already are aware of how great they are so here\'s an alternative to MailChimp if you\'re trying to keep costs down initially.\r\n\r\nThey deliver emails via Amazon SES (Simple Email Services) and I\'ve seen pretty good deliverability rates so far.\r\n\r\nAlso, you may not need all the various features with MC. They definitely both have their strengths. If you\'re going more barebones and are adept with creating automation workflows and know how to use Zapier - you can really get a lot done with Email Octopus.\r\n\r\nThis email marketing software is definitely worth checking out.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Social Media Marketing</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://buffer.com\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5050\" src=\"http://codelabstudios.com/app/uploads/2018/02/Buffer-Icon.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"41\" height=\"42\" /></a><a href=\"https://buffer.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Buffer</a></span>\r\nIf your business isn\'t on Facebook, fix that asap. Buffer\'s clean user interface and multi-platform social media scheduling wins everytime. Free to use.</span></blockquote>\r\nSchedule posts to go out on your Facebook, Google+ (ha), and Instagram all at the same time.\r\n\r\nGreat for staying on top of your social media marketing without thinking about.\r\n\r\nFacebook is starting to wisen up and include social post scheduling in their native platform but maybe it took a company like Buffer to really highlight how big the demand is for this.\r\n\r\nStaying consistent on social media, regardless of how many likes or clicks you get, is still relevant in 2017.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nothing helps you continuously grow your social media traffic organically over time like Buffer</strong>.\r\n\r\nRemember, it\'s not about how many comments are likes you get per post but how much engagement you get as a whole - so keep posting damnit!\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Project Management</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/05/Trello.png\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://trello.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Trello</a></span>\r\nDon\'t be fooled by it\'s simplicity. I have been using Trello for years. It\'s the best way to manage, well.. everything. Here\'s some <a href=\"https://trello.com/inspiration/project-management\">use cases.</a></span></blockquote>\r\nOrganizing leads, setting reminders, due dates, attachments, integrations, power-ups, plus a bunch of other cool stuff.\r\n\r\n<strong>That\'s what Trello is in a nutshell.</strong>\r\n\r\nBasically you can use to to manage any projects you have, personally I have my projects split up into different boards.\r\n\r\nFor example, you can have a board that automatically spits a new lead card into trello every time someone fills out a contact form on your website.\r\n\r\n<strong>Every time you talk to that lead, you can store all the details in a comment and set a reminder date.</strong>\r\n\r\nThere\'s actually a whole lot you can do with trello and if you\'re looking for marketing tools, I think you\'ll need this as well if you\'re not already an avid user.\r\n\r\n<strong>Oh! And it\'s free. Forgot to mention that.</strong> ?\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Opt-in Pages &amp; Conversions</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/05/Leadpages-Logo.png\" width=\"40\" /><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://www.leadpages.net/\" rel=\"nofollow\">LeadPages</a></span>\r\nThe <u>best</u> landing page builder. This one\'s pretty obvious but I included it just in case there\'s that <i>one</i> person who\'s never heard of LeadPages</span></blockquote>\r\nIf you\'re hiring some guy on Fiverr to code your landing pages since you can\'t do it yourself - <strong>Here\'s a solution to put an end to that.</strong>\r\n\r\nFor every free offer you\'re trying to send traffic to, free cheatsheet download, or sales page, Leadpages is a great alternative to coding your own landing pages by hand.\r\n\r\n<i>A landing page is typically where the visitor first lands on your website.</i>\r\n\r\nThis is often also a single page that you can\'t navigate away from unless you opt-in (although Facebook is starting to put a stop to this).\r\n\r\nThe drag and drop editor in Leadpages not only makes this super easy to understand but saves you <strong>SO MUCH TIME</strong>\r\n\r\nThe cost is reasonable for what it\'s worth compared to competitors.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\n\r\nUsing the crappy ? web software can cost you time  + money ?\r\n\r\nI\'ve spent my fair share on software as a service (SaaS) websites to know what to recommend (plus I took some suggestions from reliable sources, mentioned above).\r\n\r\nHopefully you found some useful and <strong>new applications</strong> to use that will save you money &amp; time (and more importantly frustration, R.I.P. Mittens ).\r\n\r\n<i>If you\'re a kind soul who took the time to read this far, please reach out and suggest some other topics I should cover.</i>\r\n\r\nThere are no bad suggestions!\r\n\r\n<span id=\"hint\">Except for yours David.</span>\r\n\r\nIf you have any questions or want to contact us, feel free to <a href=\"/services/\">do so here.</a>\r\n<h4>Keep up the hustle,</h4>','List of Marketing Tools for Entrepreneurs','','publish','closed','open','','marketing-apps-for-entrepreneurs','','','2018-02-14 05:30:20','2018-02-14 10:30:20','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=3987',0,'post','',0),(4191,1,'2017-08-20 16:57:47','2017-08-20 16:57:47','<header class=\"entry-header\"></header>\r\n<div class=\"entry-content content\">\r\n<div id=\"cs-content\" class=\"cs-content\">\r\n<div id=\"x-section-1\" class=\"x-section\">\r\n<div class=\"x-container max width\">\r\n<div class=\"x-column x-sm x-1-1\">\r\n<div class=\"x-text\">\r\n\r\nSo if youre interested in advertising on Facebook in 2017, you<strong>should first know</strong>about Facebook Remarketing, Why its amazing, and how to utilize it. Ill explain all of this for you below.\r\n\r\n<strong><u>The quickest way to explain it is with this example;</u></strong>\r\n\r\nImagine you walked into your local coffee shop today.\r\n\r\nFor some reason you didnt buy anything, maybe you had to take a call, your house was on fire, it can be anything. You left the shop.\r\n\r\nThat coffee shop lost a potential customer.<strong>Until now.</strong>\r\n\r\nAs youre on your way home, all the billboards you pass by, actually have your local coffee shop advertising on them.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5040 size-full\" src=\"http://codelabstudios.com/app/uploads/2018/02/Facebook-Remarketing-for-Local-Businesses-min-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"724\" height=\"451\" />\r\n\r\nNot only are you seeing their ads but youre seeing offers that are<strong>relevant and enticing to you</strong> the potential customer.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<blockquote>Now that business has more plenty of opportunities to bring you back in as a customer. Its a game-changer.</blockquote>\r\n<div id=\"x-section-1\" class=\"x-section\">\r\n<div class=\"x-container max width\">\r\n<div class=\"x-column x-sm x-1-1\">\r\n<div class=\"x-text\">\r\n\r\nBasically, Facebook can do just this, except for online advertising (and even offline to some degree).\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div id=\"x-section-2\" class=\"x-section\">\r\n<div class=\"x-container max width\">\r\n<div class=\"x-column x-sm x-1-1\">\r\n<div class=\"x-text\"></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2 id=\"Remarketing\">What is Facebook Remarketing?</h2>\r\n<strong>Facebook Remarketing refers to the strategy of displaying ads, offers, and discounts, to people that have visited your website</strong>(making them potential customers),<strong>while theyre browsing Facebook</strong>.\r\n\r\nYou can even display ads to people who have purchased from you in the past. Display up-sells, cross-sells, etc and bring them back to your site every time.\r\n\r\nAnyone that visits your website can automatically be put into whats called a<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/business/help/341425252616329\"><strong>Facebook Custom Audience</strong></a>(and then into a Remarketing List).\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"box\"><span id=\"item\"><a href=\"https://emailoctopus.com/\">What is a Facebook Custom Audience?</a></span>\r\nA Custom Audience from a customer list is a type of audience you can create made up of your existing customers. You can target ads to the audience youve created on Facebook, Instagram, and Audience Network.</span>\r\n\r\n<i>Source: Facebook Help Center</i></blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"Importance\">Why is this so important?</h2>\r\nNow heres the fun part.\r\n\r\n<strong>Anytime someone visits your website, they are anonymously saved to your custom audience.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Then, the next time they are on Facebook, they are going to see YOUR ADS in their news feed or side bar.</strong>\r\n\r\nMost people are on Facebook at some point these days, including your target customer, roughly<strong>2 billion people/month</strong>log on.\r\n\r\nSo these people seeing your ads are going to be<strong>very likely to purchase or sign up</strong>because theyve already been to your website and are most likely interested in what you have to offer.\r\n<h2 id=\"GetStarted\">How to Get Started</h2>\r\nIn order to build a custom audience from people who have purchased from you or<strong>visited your website</strong>(which are some of the best kind of people by the way  it makes sense, theyve raised their hand and shown an interest in what you have to offer as a business), you need install a<strong>Facebook Pixel</strong>.\r\n\r\n<i>*This part you might need to be a little technically inclined for or send this guide to someone who is.</i>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<blockquote>How to Install your Facebook Pixel (Free Guide)\r\n<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/business/help/952192354843755\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.facebook.com/business/help/952192354843755</a></blockquote>\r\n<i>The page will look something like this:</i>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5042 size-full\" src=\"http://codelabstudios.com/app/uploads/2018/02/Facebook-Pixel-Guide-min.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"728\" height=\"447\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2 id=\"Audience\">How to Create the Audience</h2>\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"popout\">Visit your Facebook Ads Manager\r\n<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/ads/manager/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.facebook.com/business/help/952192354843755</a></span></blockquote>\r\nOnce youre in your<strong>Facebook Ads Manager</strong>, go ahead and click on the<img src=\"https://codelabstudios.dev/app/uploads/2017/08/Hamburger.jpg\" />and follow the instructions in the images below.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-5041\" src=\"http://codelabstudios.com/app/uploads/2018/02/Steps-1-and-2-min.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"734\" height=\"268\" />\r\n\r\nAnd thats basically it for the basics on setting up a custom audience for remarketing.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"Conclusion\">Conclusion</h2>\r\nThis is just the beginners guide on<strong>what is Facebook Remarketing &amp; How to get Started</strong>. It gets complicated from here when it comes down to targeting the audience, creating ads, A/B testing campaigns, optimizing for conversions, getting people to actually buy from you, and scaling up. If youre not careful, you can waste money.\r\n<blockquote><span class=\"popout\">If Facebook Advertising sounds like something youd want to look into, give us a call and get some free advice.</span></blockquote>','What is Facebook Remarketing and is it Important?','','publish','closed','open','','what-is-facebook-remarketing','','','2018-02-14 05:22:34','2018-02-14 10:22:34','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=4191',0,'post','',0),(4356,2,'2017-08-26 02:27:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','How to regain SSH access to your Digital Ocean server','','draft','open','open','','','','','2017-08-26 02:27:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=4356',0,'post','',0),(4357,2,'2017-08-26 02:37:43','2017-08-26 02:37:43','Hosting and server management can be a pain for web developers, since we our daily interaction with a server consists of deploying code via Bitbucket or Github. We basically rarely ever SSH into the server with the terminal or use SFTP to upload files (at least you shouldn\'t, git version control is a much better way to deploy your files to the cloud).\n\nSo here\'s what happened. My Macbook Pro\'s flash SSD died on me, and my Time Machine was not connected to my home network for months and I hadn\'t notice. I lost lots of files, but most importantly, my ~/.ssh/id_rsa and ~/.ssh_id_rsa.pub were missing too! I made no backups on Google Drive or Dropbox because it\'s not secure practice to do that. But what are the chances someone\'s going to steal my key from the cloud, and also know the IP address of my Digital Ocean servers. In hindsight, I should have just backed them up. Actually there\'s a popular repo Mackup, which is a tool that syncs your Mac settings to dropbox. Settings could include your ~/.bashrc, ~/.bash_profile, keyboard bindings, etc. They had backed up ~/.ssh directory by default, but after some people saying that isn\'t a good practice, they ignored that directory since then.\n\nFirst step is to log into your Digital Ocean account, then click on the \'Access Console\' button. You\'ll be given a prompt asking for your login. Username is \"root\", and password is your server password. You can request a new password if you forgot your old once. Once you login, you\'ll want to navigate to ~/.ssh/authorized_keys.\n\nThis file stores all the public keys that could access the server.','How to regain SSH access to your Digital Ocean server','','draft','open','open','','regain-ssh-access-digital-ocean-server','','','2017-08-26 02:37:43','2017-08-26 02:37:43','',0,'https://codelabstudios.dev/?p=4357',0,'post','',0),(5036,1,'2017-09-18 17:51:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00','[cs_content][cs_section parallax=\"false\" separator_top_type=\"none\" separator_top_height=\"50px\" separator_top_angle_point=\"50\" separator_bottom_type=\"none\" separator_bottom_height=\